  "topology_context": {
    "GBM_vs_NSCLC_flip": "In NSCLC, mTOR was the damper (+0.049), MEK1 was the anchor (-0.011). In GBM, mTOR is the anchor (-0.093) and MEK1 is the damper (+0.099). This is a topology flip — same two drugs but opposite structural positions.",
    "GBM_vs_CRC_same": "In CRC, MEK1 was the damper (+0.120), mTOR was the anchor (-0.117). In GBM, MEK1 is also the damper (+0.099), mTOR is also the anchor (-0.093). Same topology as CRC — GBM and CRC are in the same structural regime for MEK/mTOR.",
    "mTOR_4cancer_series": "Monotonic mTOR efficacy prediction: NSCLC (damper +0.049) most effective, PDAC (weak anchor -0.075) 2nd, GBM (intermediate anchor -0.093) 3rd, CRC (strong anchor -0.117) least effective. GBM predicts: mTOR LFC between -0.434 (PDAC) and -0.270 (CRC).",
    "EGFR_anchor_insight": "EGFR is the primary GBM oncogene but is a structural ANCHOR (delta_r=-0.111). This is consistent with ODS: the anchor is the integration hub of both layers; removing it disrupts network coupling. EGFR inhibitors have failed in GBM clinical trials (ascribed to BBB), but PRISM is in vitro — if EGFR is an anchor, ODS predicts EGFR inhibitors should also be LESS effective in vitro, even without BBB confounding.",
    "STAT3_biggest_anchor": "STAT3 is the biggest structural anchor in GBM (delta_r=-0.155). This makes biological sense — STAT3 is the core GBM stem cell hub, activating MYC, VEGF, BCL-2. But there are no STAT3 inhibitors in PRISM 20Q2, so this cannot be directly tested."
  },
  "hypotheses": [
    {
      "id": "h1",
      "statement": "Spearman r(delta_r, mean PRISM LFC) < -0.40 across 6 druggable cytotoxic nodes (MET, MEK1, AKT1, PI3K, mTOR, EGFR) within EGFR-dep glioma lines (EGFR Chronos < -0.5). delta_r range: +0.185 (MET, damper) to -0.111 (EGFR, anchor). Predicted ordering: MET > MEK1 > AKT1 > PI3K > mTOR > EGFR (more negative LFC = more killing)."
    },
    {
      "id": "h2",
      "label": "Topology flip test (GBM: same regime as CRC)",
      "statement": "MEK1 mean PRISM LFC < mTOR mean PRISM LFC within EGFR-dep glioma lines (MEK1 kills more than mTOR, same topology as CRC). MEK1 is structural DAMPER (+0.099) in GBM; mTOR is structural ANCHOR (-0.093). In NSCLC: mTOR was the damper → mTOR killed more (CONFIRMED). In CRC: MEK1 was the damper → MEK1 killed more (CONFIRMED). In GBM: MEK1 is the damper again → predicts MEK1 kills more than mTOR."
    },
    {
      "id": "h3",
      "label": "mTOR 4-cancer monotonic test (prospective)",
      "statement": "mTOR mean PRISM LFC in GBM is between PDAC ref (-0.434) and CRC ref (-0.270). That is: -0.434 < mTOR_GBM_LFC < -0.270. GBM mTOR is an anchor (delta_r=-0.093), intermediate between PDAC (-0.075) and CRC (-0.117). The 3-cancer monotonic trend predicts GBM mTOR falls in the intermediate range. PDAC ref: outputs/D3_PDAC_v1_results.json mTOR mean_lfc=-0.434. CRC ref: outputs/D3_CRC_v1_results.json mTOR mean_lfc=-0.270."
    },
    {
      "id": "h4",
      "label": "EGFR anchor in vitro test",
      "statement": "EGFR inhibitors in EGFR-dep glioma lines show mean PRISM LFC > -0.400 (relatively weak killing, consistent with anchor structural position delta_r=-0.111). Counterintuitive prediction: even in EGFR-essential cells, EGFR inhibitors kill less efficiently than MEK1 inhibitors, because EGFR is an anchor (structural integrator) not a damper. This would establish that in vitro EGFR inhibitor failure is partly structural (topology), not only pharmacological (BBB)."
    }
  ],
